\[en] title: TRACEE\-LIST\-FILTERABLE section: 1 header: Tracee List
Filterable Command Manual date: 2026/07 \&...
.SS NAME
tracee \f[B]list filterable\f[R] \- Show which event fields filter in
the kernel vs user space
.SS SYNOPSIS
tracee \f[B]list filterable\f[R] <event\&...> [\-\-json]
.PP
tracee \f[B]list filterable\f[R] <policy\-path\&...> [\-\-config FILE]
[\-\-json]
.PP
tracee \f[B]list filterable\f[R] \-\-policy PATH [\-\-policy PATH\&...]
[\-\-config FILE] [\-\-json]
.SS DESCRIPTION
The \f[B]list filterable\f[R] command shows where each of an event\[cq]s
filters is enforced.
.PP
Kernel filters drop non\-matching instances \f[B]before\f[R] the event
is submitted (the cheapest filtering); user\-space filters run
\f[B]after\f[R] submission (the event is collected, then filtered).
Scope filters (\f[B]comm\f[R], \f[B]uid\f[R], \f[B]pid\f[R],
\f[B]mntns\f[R], \f[B]pidns\f[R], \&...)
and the \f[B]pathname\f[R] data filter are kernel\-enforced; other data
fields and return\-value filters run in user space.
.PP
The command has two modes.
.SS STATIC MODE
Given one or more event names, classify each event\[cq]s fields as
kernel\- or user\-space\-filterable:
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable security_file_open
tracee list filterable sched_process_exec security_file_open \-\-json
.EE
.SS POLICY\-AWARE MODE
Given a policy file or directory (detected automatically) or
\f[B]\-\-policy\f[R], the real rule set is computed \- dependency
expansion, bootstrap selections, cross\-policy union, and overflow \-
and, per selected event, the report states whether in\-kernel filtering
is \f[B]effective\f[R], \f[B]defeated\f[R] by a broad (unfiltered)
co\-selector of the same event, or lost to \f[B]overflow\f[R] (an event
selected by more than 64 rules, which the kernel must submit in full).
Per\-policy attribution and a hint are included where relevant.
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable ./policies
tracee list filterable ./my\-policy.yaml
tracee list filterable \-\-policy ./p1.yaml \-\-policy ./p2.yaml \-\-json
.EE
.SS OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-\-policy\f[R] PATH
Analyze policy file(s) or director(ies) instead of listing an
event\[cq]s fields.
Repeatable.
A positional policy path is detected automatically, so this flag is
optional.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-config\f[R] FILE
A Tracee config file whose settings affect the report.
The configured detectors\[cq] declared base\-event scope filters are
folded in, and the DNS cache force\-collects \f[B]net_packet_dns\f[R].
Process\-store and capture settings add only internal control\-plane
events (a separate perf buffer), so they do not change the report.
Without \f[B]\-\-config\f[R] the policies are analyzed on their own.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-json\f[R], \f[B]\-j\f[R]
Output in JSON format for scripting.
.SS EXAMPLES
.IP \[bu] 2
Classify a single event\[cq]s fields:
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable security_file_open
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Classify several events as JSON:
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable sched_process_exec security_file_open \-\-json
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Analyze a policy directory:
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable ./policies
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Analyze specific policy files:
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable \-\-policy ./p1.yaml \-\-policy ./p2.yaml
.EE
.IP \[bu] 2
Analyze policies in the context of a real scenario (detectors and DNS
cache):
.IP
.EX
tracee list filterable ./policies \-\-config /etc/tracee/tracee.yaml
.EE
